158. 
<taxonomicName id="7D7D0D4D0F4A01E979B70E849D3CEAC6" LSID="860EB3D4-1EC9-503F-BBC7-454BAF9A8DD0" authority="Greuter, Bauhinia 3: 251. 1967. (Greuter 1967: 251)." authorityName="Greuter, Bauhinia 3: 251. 1967. (Greuter" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus argyrothamnos" order="Solanales" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="argyrothamnos">Convolvulus argyrothamnos Greuter, Bauhinia 3: 251. 1967. (Greuter 1967: 251).</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="97189E7E9B96985589662C624CE40B6F" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="type">
<paragraph id="FEE00C0929E86A62B58540A105C9E70E" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AFAC7B33A3DDA6DFBA9F6BFC727E7A4F" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">
GREECE, Crete, 
<normalizedToken id="43C92B673C0417101BA45B328171ADD1" originalValue="IerÃ¡petra">Ierapetra</normalizedToken>
. 
<emphasis id="A933ACE59570A938F982E4C56F641E58" italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Greuter</emphasis>
7802 (holotype Hb. Greuter (B or PAL?); isotypes E00288017!, G, LD, W!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="98F4AEF60F1E06B1D12F4DE5CAE28832" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="distinguishing features">
<paragraph id="CFE878C35A4AF73E6AB19FE0F5C531D6" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Distinguishing features.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B393B74C620BDA3D2B390FE46EF5BF76" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">
Undershrub clearly related to 
<taxonomicName id="EEF9AEFA38C4134373F05B94C1183AEF" authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 552. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus oleifolius" order="Solanales" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oleifolius">
<emphasis id="1E4C92C4D2BD19184D8415988EDB6AB7" italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Convolvulus oleifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and distinguished by its unusual habit. It is a pendulous plant, strongly acrotonous in its branching with the leaves in fasciculate bunches. No floral differences from 
<taxonomicName id="D805902B9E3A9A1A522E301555D9CA54" authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 552. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus oleifolius" order="Solanales" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oleifolius">
<emphasis id="2010DEF4FB925BA21A07187E5BD07E76" italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Convolvulus oleifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4ACF98E5731A0216E830B94C73795527" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="description">
<paragraph id="45386377F908E42B6A15F6DBB04A6605" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="374FE6FA4C12FEF6D1C794B9B5E7154F" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Endemic to Crete.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="17B4AABA779473B439AA55C0159FAB7A" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" type="notes">
<paragraph id="40D5D007900F559B40DDA8C905AEC288" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1C630FA7EB4FE9F28F01814CF74158D7" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">
It is impossible to confirm whether this is a distinct relict species or some peculiar adaptation of 
<taxonomicName id="F72E08B7D696C55F489D79F4958A51E3" authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 552. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus oleifolius" order="Solanales" pageId="169" pageNumber="170" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oleifolius">
<emphasis id="D3783E8FB71F66D2F0916D4C55BFE963" italics="true" pageId="169" pageNumber="170">Convolvulus oleifolius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to the cliff habitat. Its population is apparently restricted to a small number of plants on one or two limestone cliffs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
